December, 2017. An methodology to evaluate the conditions of noise exposure:
an study of ornamental stone processing industries.. Adviser: Antônio Cleber
Gonçalvez Tibiriçá. Co-Adviser: Luciano José Minette.
The acoustics, area of knowledge in which physical phenomena related to sound are stud-
ied, has its concepts little explored and applied in the field of Architecture and Urbanism.
In general, when architects consider this field, they do so to mitigate, mainly, situations
of speech intelligibility inside the environments. In addition, the poor interaction between
knowledge areas and professional activity that demands connections between Architecture
and Hygiene and Occupational Safety, has a direct and negative impact on the project
quality and people?s lives, especially when it comes to build environments with industrial
purposes. From the point of view of occupational risk, noise causes different health dam-
age, often detected too late. Based on this study, this work proposes a methodology for
evaluation of sound exposure conditions and recommendations with the use of architec-
tural, urbanistic and occupational safety solutions related to auditory comfort, oriented by
the noise norms and laws, to mitigate these risks, to which people from diverse population
groups are exposed, in order to contribute to the filling of the existing gap in noise control
at the Occupational Architecture. For validation of this work, case studies were made in
ornamental stone processing industries, held in the city of Cachoeiro de Itapemirim, ES,
the largest industrial pole of this sector in Brazil. By means of collection and treatment
of data about the sound exposure conditions and the confrontation of these data with
the current legislation, the sound manifestations resulting from the process of ornamental
stone processing were evidenced, characterizing them as sources of noise pollution in the
community and a harmful agent to the health of the worker, situation caused mainly by
project negligence.
